caption: b'If you\xe2\x80\x99re planning a major purchase or financing a gift soon, be sure to unfreeze your credit. You can temporarily lift your credit freeze by choosing how long you want your credit unfrozen. Then you don\xe2\x80\x99t have to remember to refreeze it later.'

b'Your credit limit, that is. This is the available credit you have on your revolving accounts like credit cards. If you use too much of your limit, it could temporarily lower your credit score until your balances are paid down.'

b'Inquiries happen when a company or person requests to see your credit report. Not just anyone can check your report. They have to have what is called a permissible purpose to do so. Read about the different types of inquiries and how they impact your credit score through the link in our bio.'
b'There are some big ways to help your score, like consistently making payments on time and keeping balances low. But even small moves, supported by good habits, can help over time.'

b'If you use your credit card more during shopping season, make sure to check your transaction history frequently. This will help stay on top of any suspicious activity. If you notice a charge you didn\xe2\x80\x99t authorize, contact your card issuer immediately.'

b'Our study shows 15% of financially impacted people plan to refinance or renegotiate payment rates to help pay bills and loans. If you plan to refinance, bunching your loan applications may help limit the negative impact to your credit score. Learn more about rate shopping and your credit in our blog post (link in bio).'

b'Our Financial Hardship Studies have found COVID-related digital fraud is on the rise. If you think you are a victim of fraud, it may be a good idea to add a fraud alert to your credit report. A fraud alert tells lenders to take extra steps to confirm your identity before extending credit.'

b'Closing a credit card can be a smart financial move, but closing a card may cause changes to your credit information that could lower your score. For a more detailed explanation about why credit scores may drop, check out the blog post in our bio.'

b'Closing a credit card can be a smart financial move, but closing a card may cause changes to your credit information that could lower your score. For a more detailed explanation about why credit scores may drop, check out the blog post in our bio.'

b'When you look at your accounts in your credit report, you\xe2\x80\x99ll see a line that tells you what type of account it is. Types can be revolving, like a credit card, or installment, like a student or auto loan. Understanding your account types is important as you continue to manage your credit report information. Learn more about the difference between revolving and installment accounts through the link in our bio. \n#readingyourcreditreport'

b'Today we recognize Veterans Day in the U.S. \xe2\x80\x93 a time to celebrate and honor military men and women for their leadership, loyalty and sacrifices for our country. As a company that values the diversity of people, including our veteran community, we observe this important day with great pride for all service members and their families around the globe, and thank those who have helped protect our freedoms.'

b'Becoming an authorized user on a parent\xe2\x80\x99s credit card may allow you to share in the history of the account activity. If that option doesn\xe2\x80\x99t work for you, a secured credit card, which requires an upfront deposit, can help build your credit history as well. For more details, check out our blog (link in bio).'

b'Believe it or not, the holidays are right around the corner. It\xe2\x80\x99s never too early to start making a plan to save and make the holidays less financially stressful. To help, try to estimate how much you\xe2\x80\x99ll spend this year and break that into manageable chunks you can save until you need it.'

b'Almost one in five financially impacted Americans are concerned about paying a personal loan bill. If you\xe2\x80\x99re worried you may miss a payment, your lender may offer assistance. Our blog post has more information about getting the help you need. (link in bio).'

b'Even if you feel you don\xe2\x80\x99t have a lot to steal right now, it\xe2\x80\x99s important to manage your data identity like you would any other high-value asset. The good credit history you\xe2\x80\x99re working to build will allow you to take advantage of future opportunities. Protect what you\xe2\x80\x99re building now so fraudsters can\xe2\x80\x99t use your data to capture those opportunities for themselves.'

b'Our recent study shows financial accommodations have benefitted Americans in need. Watch our video to learn more about how accommodations have helped people manage their household budgets in 2020 and find resources to help you manage your financial health.'

b'We know everyone\xe2\x80\x99s busy and it can feel like yet another thing to add to your list, but monitoring your credit is a crucial step to managing your data identity. You don\xe2\x80\x99t need to obsess over it, but try to check in consistently so you can spot any unexpected changes.'

b'College isn\xe2\x80\x99t usually a time of wealth building, but it\xe2\x80\x99s a perfect time to practice sound financial habits. It\xe2\x80\x99s really important to know how much money you currently have or will have coming in so you can make it last. This could be from student loans, money you saved or income from a part-time job. Break that down for each month of the semester. 
Then, figure out what you\xe2\x80\x99ll need to spend each month to keep you going and motivated throughout the semester. You don\xe2\x80\x99t have to cut every single thing out of your budget that\xe2\x80\x99s not \xe2\x80\x9cnecessary.\xe2\x80\x9d If you like your daily lattes, you can keep them. But if you\xe2\x80\x99re going to make this money last, there are some things like shopping splurges and dinners out that you may need to cut back on.
Finally, use your school resources. You may have prepaid for a number of things, like meal plans and gym memberships. There are other resources universities provide that can save you money, like free or reduced-cost digital services or public transportation. Plus, there are many local and online student discounts.
If you have specific questions about funding your education, talk to your school\xe2\x80\x99s financial resource officers.'

b'One-third of financially impacted Millennials are concerned about their cell phone bills. Many carriers offer payment arrangements for those worried about making payments on time. You can start some of these payment plans with your carrier online.'

b'If your personal data has been compromised, a credit freeze can help keep your credit safe. A freeze keeps lenders from accessing your credit report, preventing anyone from opening new accounts in your name. Freezing is free, and unfreezing is easy when needed.'

b'If you share an account with a partner, it may be listed on both of your credit reports. But it\xe2\x80\x99s likely you both have other individual accounts and credit history that are unique to you. Because of this, your scores can be different.'

b'A home inspection is an important part of a new home purchase. But inspecting your own credit reports is important too. Lenders will look at your credit before making a lending decision, so make sure your credit data is complete and accurate before you start shopping to help things go as smoothly as possible. \nWhat tips do you have for first-time homebuyers?'

b'When you look at your credit card accounts on your report, you\xe2\x80\x99ll see a month-by-month breakdown of the account\xe2\x80\x99s balance; how much money, if any, is past due; and the rating or status. In the example account pictured here, the rating is \xe2\x80\x9cok,\xe2\x80\x9d which means payments are current. \nCredit reports have a lot of information in them, so they may seem confusing. But the more you review your reports, the easier it gets!\nWe\xe2\x80\x99ll continue to provide quick examples to help using the hashtag #readingyourcreditreport.'

b'Could you live without your daily afternoon coffee run? Probably. But if it\xe2\x80\x99s a small cost that brings you big value or joy, you may not want to cut it. Try to find big things with little value to cut if you\xe2\x80\x99re managing a tight budget. \nOur Consumer Financial Hardship Studies have shown that financially impacted Americans are currently cutting back on discretionary spending. Are there any items you\xe2\x80\x99re looking to slash from your budget? Maybe you use Wi-Fi most of the time, so you can adjust your phone plan? If you need to, see if you can change something that won\xe2\x80\x99t affect your day-to-day much. \nWhat are some of your favorite budgeting tips?'

b'Lenders can choose to report to one, two or all three nationwide agencies. This means the information in your reports may vary. Since credit scores are based on information on your report, differences in report information may be one reason you could see different credit scores from the reporting agencies.'

b'The score you get when you check it on TransUnion\xe2\x80\x99s site is based on VantageScore:registered: 3.0. This \xe2\x80\x9cgood\xe2\x80\x9d range is a guide. There are various types of credit scores and VantageScore 3.0 may not be the score used by your lender.\nNo matter where your score stands now, you can take action to build good credit health habits so you can achieve your goal score over time. Learn more in the link in our bio.'
b'Your credit scores are calculated based on factors including your history of managing debt. Demographic information isn\xe2\x80\x99t used to calculate a score.'

b'Digital fraud related to COVID-19 is on the rise, as seen in our Consumer Financial Hardship Studies. Help protect your valuable data identity from would-be fraudsters by taking action. Learn more about how to help keep your credit safe by visiting the link in our bio.'

b'Account responsibility is pretty much what it sounds like\xe2\x80\x94it\xe2\x80\x99ll tell you who is responsible for paying off the account. For the mortgage in the image, it\xe2\x80\x99s listed as a joint account. So this person opened the mortgage with another person. This account would show on that person\xe2\x80\x99s credit report as well.\nIf you\xe2\x80\x99re the only person listed on the account, the responsibility line would read \xe2\x80\x9cindividual.\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x9cAuthorized\xe2\x80\x9d means you\xe2\x80\x99re an authorized user on the account, but not responsible for its repayment. \nNo matter the responsibility, being aware of all the accounts on your report is important. We\xe2\x80\x99ll continue to break down credit reports in these bite-sized chunks. You can follow along through the hashtag #readingyourcreditreport.'

b'If you pay off a balance or close an account, you may hope to see it reflected in your credit reports and scores immediately. Your TransUnion credit report is updated when lenders provide the information to us. Lenders generally report to us once a month, so don\xe2\x80\x99t be alarmed if you don\xe2\x80\x99t see changes right away.'

b'Answer: Talk to your lenders. \n\nIf you\xe2\x80\x99ve lost your job and are struggling to make payments, your lenders may have relief plans available. b'Our Financial Hardship Study showed that those who\xe2\x80\x99ve lost their jobs due to COVID-19 expect to be short $1004.50 on upcoming bills. Losing a job doesn\xe2\x80\x99t affect your credit, but missing a payment can. \nLearn how to protect your credit if you\xe2\x80\x99ve lost your job at the link in our bio.'

b'Our latest study shows one in five financially impacted Americans are increasing use of their available credit to help manage their household budget. b'Phishing happens when a fraudster tries to trick you into giving them your personal information by impersonating a person or company you know. It\xe2\x80\x99s also the most common fraud scheme reported among people who\xe2\x80\x99ve been targeted by COVID-19 related digital fraud, according to our recent financial hardship study.\nAlways be cautious with links and attachments in emails and texts if you\xe2\x80\x99re not sure who the sender is. And if you get a suspicious email, you may want to contact the company for clarification.'

b'When making a plan to pay off debt, a good place to start is with your credit report. This can help you prioritize which debts you\xe2\x80\x99ll attack first. Through April 2021, you can get your credit reports for free online weekly at annualcreditreport.com (link in bio).'

b'Credit utilization is an important factor in calculating your credit scores. Paying down big balances helps a lot.\nCredit utilization measures how much of your available credit you\xe2\x80\x99re currently using. Generally, you should try to use less than 30% percent of your available credit. Getting as close to 0% as possible is ideal. Creating a spending and savings plan to pay down debt can help your monthly cash flow and help you make gains toward healthy credit. #newyearnewyou #newyearsresolutions #healthycredit'

b'Think of a credit freeze as a gate around your credit, helping protect it from unwanted access. 
A credit freeze blocks lenders from accessing your credit report to open a new account, which guards against identity theft. If you start shopping for a new line of credit, you\xe2\x80\x99ll need to temporarily lift or permanently unfreeze your credit. You\xe2\x80\x99re in control \xe2\x80\x93 you can freeze, lift or unfreeze any time. Plus, it\xe2\x80\x99s free and won\xe2\x80\x99t affect your credit score. 
This may be the only time this winter you\xe2\x80\x99ll be happy something is frozen. 
To learn more about freezing your credit, use the link in our bio! #creditfreeze #winter #credit #personalfinance'

b'Before opening or closing any credit cards in 2020, do your research on your current cards and their benefits. \nDo one or more of your cards have an annual fee that you could live without? Determine which cards are useful and which may be busting your budget. If you\xe2\x80\x99re getting limited use out of a high annual fee card, you may want to consider canceling it. But if the card has no annual fee or if you get a lot of value out of it, it could be worth keeping it open, especially if it\xe2\x80\x99s an older account. Longstanding credit accounts help build credit health, as they demonstrate a responsible credit history. \nTo learn more about how canceling a credit card will impact your credit score, head to the link in our bio! #newyearnewyou #creditcards #creditcardrewards'
